In SpriteBatcher.DrawBatch, _batchItemList.Sort(CompareTexture) is used to sort the list on Texture. CompareTexture however is defined as such:

static int CompareTexture(SpriteBatchItem a, SpriteBatchItem b)
{
    return ReferenceEquals(a.Texture, b.Texture) ? 0 : 1;
}

As far as I know the Sort(System.Comparison) works the same as the IComparable based sort. In the doc regarding IComparable.CompareTo it states: "If A.CompareTo(B) returns a value other than zero, then B.CompareTo(A) must return a value of the opposite sign." Which is probably the reason why SpriteSortMode.Texture doesn't actually sort the list (and therefore will cause excessive draw calls).

http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.icomparable.compareto.aspx

Related to #3262 I suspect. 

Sometimes the first call to Video.GetTexture returns Null. its easy to detect and ignore but its a change from XNA which never appears to return Null at least when the video is playing.

I added `if (_videoPlayer.State == MediaState.Playing)` to the code and the first frame was still Null.

Note: ~~Need to document what XNA does when a video is paused or stopped - does it return a null, the current (first) frame, or what?~~
- XNA never returns null even if GetTexture is called right after .Play _[MonoGame on windowsDx returns null for a few frames even after State is set to Playing]_
- If .Play has not been called GetTexture throws InvalidOperationException("Operation is not valid due to the current state of the object.") _[MonoGame returns null]_
- If you allow the video to run to the end GetTexture returns the final frame even when .State changes to Stopped
- If you call .Pause or .Stop GetTexture returns the frame you paused/stopped on
- You can call Resume/Pause/Stop on a player with no video and it does nothing _[MonoGame also returns doing nothing]_

Solutions:
- Make GetTexture wait till a frame is available (this code also fixes the null vs exception issue). This works on Windows DX

```
            if (_currentVideo == null)
                throw new InvalidOperationException("Operation is not valid due to the current state of the object");

            //XNA never returns a null texture
            const int timeOutMs = 500;
            Texture2D texture;
            var timer = new Stopwatch();
            timer.Start();
            do
            {
                texture = PlatformGetTexture();
                if (timer.ElapsedMilliseconds > timeOutMs)
                {
                    throw new InvalidOperationException("Platform returned a null texture");
                }
            } while (texture == null);
            return texture;
```
- Document as a difference and require people to check for null before using the texture

It seems the in XNA Video.Play will only return once Video.State has switched to .Playing 

In MonoGame you can call Video.Play and Video.State will return .Stopped 

Scenarios like this will break

```
Update()
{
          Video.Play(...);
          .....
          if (Video.State == MediaState.Stopped)
          {
              ...video done, do something else
          }
}
```

Possible fixes?
- Add the following to Video.Play - this seems to work (though I don't like the argument exception - we need a MediaException)

```
            // XNA doesn't return until the video is playing
            const int timeOutMs = 500;
            var timer = new Stopwatch();
            timer.Start();
            while (State != MediaState.Playing && timer.ElapsedMilliseconds < timeOutMs)
            {
            }
            if (State != MediaState.Playing)
            {
                //We timed out - attempt to stop to fix any bad state
                Stop();
                throw new ArgumentException("cannot start video");
            }
```
- Document this as a difference from XNA and require the caller program to add code to wait for Video.State to change

Notes:
1. that Video.State is not implemented properly on some platforms so this may not be possible to detect.
1. This might also apply to MediaPlayer
